Latitude vs X¶

This notebook utilizes the openweathermap.org API to get weather data from random cities all over the globe. That data is then output as a CSV and plotted with MatPlotLib.

Dependencies¶

In [1]:
# Dependencies and Setup
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
import requests
import time
import json

# Import API key
from api_keys import api_key

# Incorporated citipy to determine city based on latitude and longitude
from citipy import citipy

Generate Cities List¶

In [2]:
# Lists for holding lat_lngs and cities
lat_lngs = []
cities = []

# Creates a set of random lat and lng combinations
lats = np.random.uniform(low=-90.000, high=90.000, size=100000)
lngs = np.random.uniform(low=-180.000, high=180.000, size=100000)
lat_lngs = zip(lats, lngs)

# Identifies the nearest city for each lat and lng combination
for lat_lng in lat_lngs:
    city = citipy.nearest_city(lat_lng[0], lat_lng[1]).city_name
    
    # If the city is unique it gets added to the cities list
    if city not in cities:
        cities.append(city)

# Print the city count to confirm sufficient count
len(cities)
Out[2]:
8876

API Calls¶

In [3]:
# Base URL and city dataframe setup
base_url = "https://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/weather?q="
cities_df = pd.DataFrame(columns=["City", "Cloudiness", "Country", "Date", "Humidity", "Lat", "Lng", "Max Temp", "Wind Speed"])

# Variable for when the city number is printed
city_num = 1

# Loops through all cities in the list
for city in cities:
    
    # Query URL & response
    q_url = f"{base_url}{city}&units=imperial&appid={api_key}"
    response = requests.get(q_url).json()
    
    # Exception for when a city isn't found
    try:
        # Prints the number and name of the city, then updates the city number variable
        print(f'City {city_num}: {json.dumps(response["name"])}')
        city_num += 1
        
        # Appends all the info of the current city to the city dataframe
        cities_df = cities_df.append({"City": json.dumps(response["name"]),
                                      "Country": json.dumps(response["sys"]["country"]),
                                      "Cloudiness": json.dumps(response["clouds"]["all"]),
                                      "Date": json.dumps(response["dt"]),
                                      "Humidity": json.dumps(response["main"]["humidity"]),
                                      "Lat": json.dumps(response["coord"]["lat"]),
                                      "Lng": json.dumps(response["coord"]["lon"]),
                                      "Max Temp": json.dumps(response["main"]["temp_max"]),
                                      "Wind Speed": json.dumps(response["wind"]["speed"])
                                     }, ignore_index=True)
            
        # Sleeps for .7 seconds to keep the API calls just over 1 per second to avoid rate limiting
        time.sleep(.7)
              
    except KeyError:
        print("City not found...")
        time.sleep(.7)

Convert Raw Data to DataFrame and Export to CSV¶

In [4]:
# Converts the number strings into floats
cities_df[["Cloudiness", "Humidity", "Lat", "Lng", "Max Temp", "Wind Speed"]] = cities_df[["Cloudiness", "Humidity", "Lat", "Lng", "Max Temp", "Wind Speed"]].astype(float)

# Writes the dataframe to a csv
cities_df.to_csv("cities_dataframe.csv")

# Creates a scatter plot from the dataframe and makes the makers look pretty
cities_df.plot(kind="scatter", x="Lat", y="Max Temp", s=40, color="steelblue", edgecolor="black", alpha=.5, figsize=(14,10))
# Labels and grid

plt.xlabel("Latitude")
plt.ylabel("Max Temperature (F)")
plt.grid()
# Saves the image and shows the plot
plt.savefig("Lat_vs_MaxTemp.png")
plt.show()
